m:properties.d:SessionName: Data Classification and Predictive Analysis with Azure Machine Learning
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Data classification help us to categorize our data and find out the insight patterns of the data. Later we can use categorized data for predictive analysis. Azure ML studio has over 30 built in classic machine learning algorithms. We just need to provide data, drag and drop different components to analyze our data and find patterns. In this session, I’ll focus on data classification algorithms, features, future data point prediction and at the end will show a complete demo of creating an azure ML application in front of the audience. No previous data analysis, machine learning, azure application development experience required to attend this session.
m:properties.d:SessionTrack: AI Machine Learning and Data Science

m:properties.d:SessionName: Become a Power BI superstar under 1 hour !
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Power BI is Microsoft's industry leading data analytics discovery and visualization tool that has disrupted the way data professionals interact and derive insights from their data. It is one of the most in-demand and sought-after tools to know in today's IT career market. Join us for a fun and interactive learning opportunity to learn how to ingest, transform and visualize data from a wide variety of sources using Power BI. Learn how to create rich and interactive reports incorporating slicers, drill-down and drill-through actions. Attendees will also learn how to create, publish and share reports and dashboards for desktop and mobile consumption. Attendees will walk-away feeling like real Power BI *superstars, capable of tackling any data project in their paths! *Awesomeness may vary.

m:properties.d:SessionName: PowerBI and PowerApps Married at First Sight
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: PowerBI is Microsoft's self service reporting tool that give businesses a robust visualization of their data. As Microsoft's Power Platform has evolved, PowerApps is taking a similar approach by providing businesses with a self service application tier. In this session we will see the power of bringing the two together. Let's explore how the visualization tier of PowerBI can enhance the development and capabilities of PowerApps. We will go from a blank canvas app and import visualizations while pointing out some of the pros and cons of marrying the two together. We will use the capabilities of PowerApps to write and update our SQL Server tables. Bringing the two together can provide businesses with a robust solution under one umbrella. Join me in learning how these two services came together and said "I DO".

m:properties.d:SessionName: Feeding the modern data warehouse (Power BI, Azure Data Factory and Databricks)
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: When it comes to feed the modern data warehouse in Azure, we're facing new challenges. This session will explain what id the modern data warehouse and how it can be fed using ETL 2.0 methodologies. Topics like Common Data Model and services will also be talked and demonstrated.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Power BI Report Server for the enterprise
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Power BI Report server allows you to share Power BI vizualisations on-premises as well as paginated reports. In this session, weèll cover the various possibilities of Power BI Report Server as a portal for your enterprise reports and we'll compare it to its counterpart in the clouds.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Building your Microsoft Business Intelligence (MSBI) Career
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Are you excited to know about the MSBI tools and work as a Business Intelligence Professional, a dynamic and rewarding career in Information Technology? If yes, this is the right time and place for you. In this session, I will give you the overview of the MSBI tools (SSIS, SSRS, SSAS, Power BI, Azure Analytics). I will also provide you some insights to build the MSBI career and to leverage the learning curve in Microsoft Data Platform, based on my knowledge and experience, the proven strategies and techniques.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Effective Presentations & Storytelling for Data Professionals
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Communication can be just as important as the work done behind the scenes. In this session you will learn practical presentation advice for conveying results to a variety of audiences and stakeholders. We will walk through a real scenario of using data to tell a story, including: assessing the situation/problem, what types of visuals to use, how to demonstrate value, and eliminating noise. The presenter will share various resources for putting together a presentation including free slide deck templates and graphics. Discussion of best practices with attendees will be encouraged.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Careers, Certifications, and Diversity: What a Microsoft field employee thinks about jobs for you.
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: The world of employment is big. What are your passions? What are the types of jobs available? We will use Microsoft as a case study for what kinds and locations of jobs are available. Certifications will be discussed.i We will also talk through diversity, and how critical it is for a successful team.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Extending Power BI Reporting with Python Scipting
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Must developers use the Power BI desktop application to design the report using standard visuals and publish to the Azure Power BI service for sharing in a production environment.
Out of the box, Power BI has 29 visuals. There are an additional 200+ custom visuals that can be down loaded from "AppSource" site at Microsoft.com.
While there are many choices, you might not have the right visual that can be customized the way you want for a given business problem . How do you solve this problem?
Recently, the Power BI Service now supports Python scripting using libraries such as "matplotlib", "pandas" and "seaborn". In this presentation, we will learn how to add scripting to the desktop designer to solve that tricky business report.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Cleaning and preparing data with Pandas
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Over eight percent of a data scientist job is spent on preparing and cleaning data for a machine learning model.
Like any process, there are a series of steps that take place. These steps include loading raw data, removing outliers, replacing or deleting missing values, encoding categorical features, scaling numeric features, and saving the dataset for future use. One might even engineer a new feature to get a better estimate on the label (y) given the features (x).
At the end of the class, you will have a variety of code snippets that you can use right away.
Of course, I will talk about how to get data from SQL Server, no matter where you database lives!
m:properties.d:SessionTrack: AI Machine Learning and Data Science

m:properties.d:SessionName: Data Vault - #gooddatahoarding
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Data Vault methodology combines the best of the traditional data warehousing (star/snowflake) modeling and normalization while taking full advantage of the power of cloud data warehousing technologies. This model is capable of dealing with cross-platform data persistence as well as volatile data sources in an agile fashion. In this session we will discuss what this methodology is and the benefits it provides using some examples.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Designing for Azure Synapse Analytics Performance
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Azure Synapse Analytics (formerly Azure Data Warehouse) is not Kimball's data warehouse. This session will discuss design and data modelling considerations when creating using Azure Synapse Analytics to yield the best performance.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Are you a Power BI Newbie?
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Want to learn Power BI, and not sure where to start? This session will teach you all the basics you need to know to get started. We will discuss some of the components of Power BI Desktop such as Power Query, Power Pivot, and Power View. I will also teach you where to go to follow the latest updates, and give you a few recommended books and websites to get to the next level.

m:properties.d:SessionName: An introduction to Data Mining with SQL Server 2017
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
With the vast amount of changes that occur in our daily business environments, it becomes more and more difficult to achieve our corporate goals without some ‘lighthouse’ to guide our way. Data mining, (while not a panacea to resolve or ‘control’ the effects of these changes), can provide us with statistical trends by analyzing our data and highlighting probable outcomes.
In this hands on BEGINNERS presentation we shall be looking at Microsoft SQL Server’s Data Mining capabilities and we shall be discussing:
1) Defining what questions we want answered and how to go about this in an effective and efficient manner.
2) Creating the data model.
3) How to gather the necessary data, discussing the training and testing aspect.
4) Processing the model.
5) Extracting information from our finished model, discussing the implications of this information.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Power BI Governance: Where to Start [PAID SESSION -Eventbrite Registration]
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Given that data is exceptionally valuable, it's essential to have a balanced Power BI governance strategy: control to ensure the system is secure and trustworthy, with freedom for users to get things done without stifling productivity. This full-day session will walk through a series of problem / solution scenarios, so be ready to bring your perspective, experience, and real-life situations to discuss. Each topic we explore will involve a mix of concepts, real-world lessons learned, and implementation details. You will receive tangible recommendations for tackling Power BI governance concerns such as: workspace management, tenant settings, roles/responsibilities, securely distributing content, protecting sensitive data, improving data trustworthiness, and reducing risk while balancing the needs of self-service BI with corporate BI. We will also discuss Power BI adoption, measurable success criteria, and supporting users. This session focuses on Power BI Desktop + Power BI Service.
PowerBI Governance by Melissa Coates Registrations open at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/power-bi-governance-tickets-91447661417

m:properties.d:SessionName: Azure SQL DW: Optimization techniques to maximize performance
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Azure SQL DW is powerful MPP cluster for processing a big amount of structured data. But, it still requires optimization to maximize performance and optimize resource usage. Some techniques almost similar to what we do with our regular SQL Server, some of them not due to MPP architecture. In this session, I will cover next topics: - how to minimize the time of data loading - how to choose a right distribution type - data movement minimization - how scaling and resource class could help to improve data processing performance - maximize Column Store index performance - update statistics - partitioning strategy

m:properties.d:SessionName: Essential Skills for Authentic, Purposeful and Effective Networking
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Networking is the process of building and maintaining quality business relationships. Linda Groszyk teaches networking skills through a “social mindfulness” lens, which involves a balance of self-awareness and purposeful engagement with others. This session is focused on self-reflection and discussion in order for attendees to increase their awareness, skills, and confidence when engaged in networking opportunities. There are 4 parts to this process: Part 1: Get Clear - In this first section, we will assess our strengths and areas for growth. Part 2: Get Ready - Preparation is the key to success. In this part, we will discuss techniques for being strategic, purposeful, and prepared for any networking event. Part 3: Get Going - Participants will learn social communication and emotional regulation strategies to use when they are networking. Part 4: Get Growing - Participants will learn the type of mindset required to reflect on a networking event purposefully and with learning in mind.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Breaking the Social Code: How to be Socially Intelligent at Work
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Is there a gap between your advanced technical skills and your social-emotional intelligence? Are you or your employees experiencing challenges communicating effectively with others, participating as part of a team, managing emotional reactions, or socially connecting at work? Is this impacting your ability to get promoted, retain employees, or establish positive workplace morale or relationships? Do you want to increase your “likeability” factor for your professional growth?
If you answered yes to any of these questions, then attending this session is a must in order for you to gain a deeper understanding of why some people struggle in the “social” realm. For many people, being “social” does not come naturally and has to be explicitly taught. In this presentation, you will learn about the mindset that is required for developing new competencies, key cognitive skills needed for social success, and tools and strategies that you can apply to increase your social intelligence skills.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Introduction to Jupyter Lab using Pandas and Python
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: This talk will present an overview of the tools. 1) What are the pieces and how do the pieces fit together? -- Architecture of Jupyiter -- Using Python as a standalone tool (VS Code, PyCharm, REPL etc.) -- History and applications for Pandas 2) What are some typical uses -- Interactive development with Jupyter -- Presentations with Jupyter (examples) -- Using Pandas in place of Excel for some simple analysis (examples) 3) Where can I learn more

m:properties.d:SessionName: Even smarter chat bot with ML.NET
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Machine Learning is the future and it’s already here. There’re so many opportunities for developers to use it in a wide variety of applications. If you heard a lot about data collection and processing, creating and training models and ready to try it all yourself with the help of .NET, I’ll show you how you can use Model Builder inside your Visual Studio to do it. That model can be easily integrated into all kinds of applications including chat bots. It’ll to provide you the most accurate response for your type of data. In this session, I’ll tell you about the specifics of ML.NET and Model Builder and then show you how to integrate your custom model with an Azure Web App Bot.
m:properties.d:SessionTrack: AI Machine Learning and Data Science

m:properties.d:SessionName: Basics Data Modeling for BI Reporting
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Come learn about the basics of data modeling for your business intelligence and reporting needs. This course will cover several introductory modeling subjects, including: * Transactional vs. Analytical models * Kimball / Inman approaches * The process for designing your data model * Hierarchies / Parent-child relationships

m:properties.d:SessionName: Architecture and Querying Large Data Warehouses
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: In this Hands-on Amazon Redshift data warehouse training seminar, I will discuss everything you need to know to be able to work with Redshift or similar data warehouses. This seminar is designed for the absolute beginner, meaning no previous knowledge of Amazon Redshift is required. I will start with an introduction, learning what a data warehouse is, the benefits of Redshift, and how Redshift compares to other analytics tools. From there, I will discuss the basics of Redshift, including data loading, data distribution concepts, and basic Redshift usage. Finally, will cover advanced data warehouse SQL querying topics, such as window functions, case when statements, advanced join concepts data loading best practices, querying redshift using python and tuning query performance. Who this seminar is for: • This session is designed for beginner to intermediate, meaning no previous knowledge of Amazon Redshift is required. • Anyone wanting to learn Amazon Redshift or similar data warehouse

m:properties.d:SessionName: Simplify your Data Pipeline
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Does your data pipeline work backlog seem never ending? If so you are not alone. Increasingly the data analytics groups are finding that the data available in their Microsoft SQL Server databases or Azure Data Lakes are insufficient to complete their assignments. What's required is the ability to make all relevant data sources (S3, ADLS, HDFS and RDBM) available in one place without the need to copy or duplicate data for analytic purposes. Provide your business users with the ability to discover, curate and analyze unfamiliar data quickly with minimal engineering involvement.
In this technical session, we will demonstrate how to leverage Dremio for self service discovery, curation and query acceleration.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Lunch & Learn: Accelerate your Data Analytics with Dremio (Sponsor)
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Learn how to enable your Data Analysts to self serve their analytic data needs using The Dremio Data Lake Engine. Dremio delivers lightning-fast queries and a self-service semantic layer directly on your data lake storage. No moving data to proprietary data warehouses, no cubes, no aggregation tables or extracts. Just flexibility and control for data architects, and self-service for data consumers.
In this lunch and learn we will see how Dremio can accelerate queries with billion plus rows in a single table for sub-second response time without a lot of data engineering overhead.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Building a Peta Byte DWH with SQL 2019
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Data is growing every day. Learn how to scale your data warehouse into the peta byte size on a reasonable budget and with great performance. This session shows how to scale the system capacity without compromising on the performance.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Scaling Clustered Column Store Indexes
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
Clustered Column Store Indexes are a great tool when used correctly. This session will explain on how to plan, configure, and operate Clustered Columstore indexes to handle trillions of rows. This is done with a real world example that is in production. Avoiding mistakes in the beginning will save you lots of data wrangling over time.
Come and learn how to partition, select the right datatypes, and insert the data into a Clustered Column Store Index to achieve optimal performance results.
m:properties.d:SessionPrerequisites: Basic understanding of tables and indexes in SQL Sever

m:properties.d:SessionName: Azure Databricks = Azure + Spark + Machine Learning Collaboration
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Azure Databricks is the hottest new service being offered on Azure! Designed in collaboration with Microsoft and Databricks, the creators of Apache Spark, Azure Databricks combines the best of Databricks and Azure to help customers accelerate innovation with one-click set up, streamlined workflows and an interactive workspace that enables collaboration between data scientists, data engineers, and business analysts. Databricks was founded by the creators of the Spark big data platform to make creating creating and managing clusters a snap and provide a first class secure data science team collaboration environment. In this presentation, we'll explain key concepts and features while demonstrating this amazing service.
m:properties.d:SessionTrack: AI Machine Learning and Data Science

m:properties.d:SessionName: Using Database Analytics to Predict App Problems
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
In a session that crosses the gap between BI and Software Development, we will dive into many meaningful metrics we can collect about application databases. By collecting, aggregating, and crunching this data, we can use our BI, analytics, and visualization tools to alert on anomalies and locate app bugs that otherwise may not be found until it is too late.
What can we track? Everything from table row counts to database file IO stats to backup sizes or even wait stats. By moving these metrics into an OLAP environment and trending their change over time, we can identify when something unusual occurs that could be indicative of a software issue.
Maybe a new process was released, but archiving and cleanup steps were forgotten. Maybe an app is creating more data than it should be due to a bad join. Perhaps a preferences page performs endless no-op updates, flooding the logs with superfluous transactions. We'll tackle these challenges and more!

m:properties.d:SessionName: Modern Data Warehouse Development End to End [PAID SESSION -Eventbrite Reg]
m:properties.d:SessionDescription:
With the smorgasbord of Azure service available, how do you approach building a modern enterprise data warehouse?
In this pre-con we will be covering both architecture patterns from Microsoft and actual implementations in the industry on how to move to Azure for your data warehousing needs. We'll cover the various offerings of Azure including storage, data ingestion and orchestration, databases , NoSQL, and streaming.
We'll also cover how to analyze all of this data with tools and services like Power BI and Databricks. Finally, we'll cover strategies on how you get there; Lift-and-shift, hybrid, or brand new implementations will all be discussed.
By the end of this pre-con you should have a thorough understanding of architecting a modern enterprise data warehouse in Azure including getting those services to work together and how to use that data effectively!
Modern Data Warehouse Development End to End by Chris Seferlis and Joshua Owens Registrations open at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/modern-data-warehouse-development-end-to-end-tickets-91445819909

m:properties.d:SessionName: Power BI Architecture End-to-End
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: This session is a technical overview of Power BI architecture options. Power BI terminology and its most prominent features and functionality will also be reviewed to help attendees gain an understanding of the broad collection of tools, services, and features which represent the Power BI ecosystem.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Advanced Analytics with Modern Data Warehousing
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Conventional data analytics platforms fail to live up to the data growth. According to a recent research report, companies use <1% of unstructured and less than 50% of structured data for any decision making. Enterprises are struggling to integrated different sources of the data , store and analyze the data . They are missing out on critical business insights. The modern Analytics/BI/Data Science platform requires advance data warehousing solutions that help break data silos while providing robust security and governance and without any lock-in.
m:properties.d:SessionTrack: AI Machine Learning and Data Science

m:properties.d:SessionName: The Modern Data Warehouse and Azure
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: In this session we will discuss how Azure is changing the approach to Data Warehousing and in some pretty dramatic ways. You can expect to learn how the Microsoft Reference Architectures are enabling organizations to deploy their data warehouses with virtually limitless scale and flexibility.

m:properties.d:SessionName: Power BI: Architecture and demo
m:properties.d:SessionDescription: Wonder how to get into "Power BI"? Architecture of Power BI confusing you? Listen to George Walters discuss the architecture of Power BI from rich desktop authoring, to dashboards in the cloud. We will finish with an interactive dashboard of data.
